  "prompt": "What's the best book of Nietzsche's to start out with?",
  "response": "For those new to Nietzsche, \"Thus Spoke Zarathustra\" is often recommended as an introduction to his philosophical style, but it can be quite complex and challenging. A more accessible starting point might be:\n\n1. \"Beyond Good and Evil\" - A more straightforward exploration of his philosophical ideas about morality and values.\n\n2. \"The Gay Science\" - A more approachable work that introduces many of his key concepts in a more readable format.\n\n3. \"On the Genealogy of Morals\" - A systematic critique of moral values, which is somewhat more structured than some of his other works.\n\nMany scholars recommend \"Beyond Good and Evil\" as the best entry point for most readers, as it provides a good overview of Nietzsche's philosophical approach without being as cryptic as some of his other works. If you're completely new to philosophy, you might want to start with a secondary source or companion book that helps explain his ideas before diving directly into his original texts.",
